---
import BlogArticle from '../../components/blog/BlogArticle.astro';
import { SEO_KEYWORDS } from '../../utils/constants';
import { titleBlogDetail } from '../../utils/seo-titles';

const title = 'Macau Sauna Guide: The Six Major Venues Compared';
const description =
  "Compare Macau's six major saunas — Empire, Manhao, Shang Pin, Number Nine, Majesty and The Excellent: each venue's signature, hours and best-fit guest.";

const toc = [
  { id: 'overview', label: 'Overview table' },
  { id: 'empire', label: 'Empire Sauna' },
  { id: 'manhao', label: 'Manhao Spa' },
  { id: 'shang-pin', label: 'Shang Pin Spa' },
  { id: 'number-nine', label: 'Number Nine Spa' },
  { id: 'majesty', label: 'Majesty Spa' },
  { id: 'excellent', label: 'The Excellent Sauna' },
  { id: 'how-to-choose', label: 'How to choose, and how to book' },
];

const related = [
  { slug: 'first-timer', cat: 'Beginner Guides', title: 'Macau Sauna First-Timer Guide 2026: Flow, Venues & Booking' },
  { slug: 'prices', cat: 'Prices & Budget', title: 'Macau Sauna Prices 2026: Entry, Service Tiers & Overnight Costs Explained' },
];

const TABLE = [
  ['Venue', 'Location', 'Signature', 'Best for'],
  ['Empire Sauna', 'Macau Peninsula', 'Themed suites + water beds, no service charge', 'Guests who judge a venue by its rooms'],
  ['Manhao Spa', 'Grandview Hotel, Taipa', "Macau's biggest catwalk selection hall", 'Cotai-based guests who want the show'],
  ['Shang Pin Spa', 'Grand Lisboa Palace, Cotai', '24-hour opening, Japanese bubble bath', 'Overnighters and Cotai hotel guests'],
  ['Number Nine Spa', 'Royal Dragon Hotel, Peninsula', 'Fashion-show stage + scenario-themed rooms', 'Fans of stage atmosphere and JP/KR-style tiers'],
  ['Majesty Spa', 'Macau Peninsula', '10+ themed rooms + KTV party rooms', 'Group parties and themed-room enthusiasts'],
  ['The Excellent Sauna', 'Grand Emperor Hotel, Peninsula', 'Noon opening, scenario rooms as add-ons', 'Daytime visits, a curated shortlist'],
];
---

<BlogArticle
  seo={{
    title: titleBlogDetail(title),
    description,
    keywords: `Macau sauna comparison, six major Macau saunas, Empire Sauna, Manhao Spa, Shang Pin Spa, Number Nine Spa, Majesty Spa, The Excellent Sauna, ${SEO_KEYWORDS}`,
    image: '/images/blog04.webp',
    imageWidth: '1200',
    imageHeight: '630',
  }}
  category="Comparisons"
  title={title}
  description={description}
  meta="Relax Macau Team · Jul 2026 · 5 min read"
  image="/images/blog04.webp"
  imageAlt="Marble baths and steam inside a Macau sauna club"
  toc={toc}
  related={related}
>
  <p>
    Macau&rsquo;s sauna scene went through a shake-up heading into 2026, and the venues genuinely worth knowing now
    come down to six: Empire, Manhao, Shang Pin, Number Nine, Majesty and The Excellent. &ldquo;Which one is
    best?&rdquo; is the question we hear most, and the honest answer is that there isn&rsquo;t one — the six have
    very different personalities. Some guests are all about the rooms, some come purely for the catwalk shows, and
    some only care whether they can stay until morning. This guide profiles each venue one by one: what its
    signature is, and who it suits. Start with the overview table, then dig into the details.
  </p>
  <p>
    Pricing is structured similarly across all six: entry starts around MOP 1,000, mainstream service tiers run
    roughly 2,500–4,500, and the top Japanese/Korean tiers mostly start from 5,000 — always confirmed against the
    day&rsquo;s quote. If you&rsquo;d rather skip the homework, just tell us your budget and we&rsquo;ll match you.
  </p>

  <h2 id="overview">Overview table</h2>
  <div class="blog-table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          {TABLE[0].map((h) => <th>{h}</th>)}
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {
          TABLE.slice(1).map((row) => (
            <tr>
              {row.map((cell) => (
                <td>{cell}</td>
              ))}
            </tr>
          ))
        }
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h2 id="empire">Empire Sauna: the newest opening, built around its suites</h2>
  <p>
    Empire Sauna is currently Macau&rsquo;s newest venue, opened in mid-May 2026 with a modern-luxury-meets-oriental-zen
    design. Its bet is squarely on the rooms themselves: hotel-grade themed suites, marble baths and a signature
    water-bed room, backed by butler-style service — the experience lands closer to a night in a boutique hotel than
    a classic sauna. It runs 24 hours, allows overnight stays, and charges no 10% service fee; booking through us
    adds two free add-on services. If brand-new hardware is your priority, start here.
  </p>

  <h2 id="manhao">Manhao Spa: Macau&rsquo;s biggest catwalk hall</h2>
  <p>
    Staying in Taipa or Cotai, Manhao Spa is the natural first look — it sits in the Grandview Hotel, about five
    minutes by car from the heart of Cotai. Its signature boils down to one word: the show. The catwalk selection hall
    is the largest in Macau — several open tiers rising through a wash of cool blue light — and comes closer to a
    staged performance than anywhere else in town, while the marble lobby and mural corridors carry the
    &ldquo;regal&rdquo; theme throughout. Rooms are integrated suites that combine a bedroom with a water bed,
    headlined by the signature red water bed under a spotlight. Note the hours — 14:00–06:00, with no overnight stays
    at present; booking through us adds two free add-on services (one if you choose the Shanghai-style massage).
  </p>

  <h2 id="shang-pin">Shang Pin Spa: the answer for overnighters and Cotai guests</h2>
  <p>
    Shang Pin Spa operates inside the Grand Lisboa Palace in Cotai, with an ornate, high-end interior and modern
    facilities. Its real strength is time: open 24 hours with overnight stays allowed, and lounge recliners you can
    sleep on until morning — genuinely useful if the night runs long and you&rsquo;d rather not book another hotel
    room. The house specialty is the Japanese bubble bath, and package promotions rotate periodically — ask on the day
    for what&rsquo;s running. If you&rsquo;re staying at the Grand Lisboa Palace or anywhere in Cotai, it&rsquo;s the
    lowest-friction choice of the six.
  </p>

  <h2 id="number-nine">Number Nine Spa: a fashion show moved indoors</h2>
  <p>
    Number Nine Spa sits in the Royal Dragon Hotel in the city centre and opened in April 2026 — the first of this new
    wave to launch. There&rsquo;s a fashion-show stage with an LED screen inside, so choosing a technician plays out
    like watching a runway; the rooms are scenario-themed, with deliberate lighting and set design. Its menu leads with
    the Japanese/Korean tiers, it runs 24 hours with overnight stays, and booking through us adds two free add-on
    services. If stage atmosphere and the JP/KR route are your thing, this is the closest match.
  </p>

  <h2 id="majesty">Majesty Spa: themed rooms plus KTV, the party venue</h2>
  <p>
    Majesty Spa has arguably the most lavish interior in Macau, and its hall uses an up-close &ldquo;scenery&rdquo;
    selection format. It also owns a combination no other venue offers: more than ten elaborately built themed rooms —
    Egyptian, Chinese wedding-bed, gym-and-boxing, wedding and cosplay themes among them — plus KTV party rooms, a
    rarity in Macau. A group booking a room to sing first and then splitting off for their own plans is a play unique
    to this house. No service charge, open 24 hours, overnight stays allowed.
  </p>

  <h2 id="excellent">The Excellent Sauna: noon opening, small and curated</h2>
  <p>
    The Excellent Sauna is in the Grand Emperor Hotel&rsquo;s main building, with hours of 12:00–04:00 — among the
    earliest openings in Macau, handy for travellers with a free afternoon. It leads with newly built Japanese-theme
    rooms, and scenario rooms — DJ booth, office, cinema — are available as paid add-ons, which keeps the format
    flexible. It&rsquo;s a smaller house that deliberately runs a short, curated menu. No overnight stays — if you
    need to stay until morning, switch to a 24-hour venue like Shang Pin or Empire.
  </p>

  <h2 id="how-to-choose">How to choose, and how to book</h2>
  <p>
    The short version: pick Empire for the rooms, Manhao for the catwalk, Shang Pin for overnights or a Cotai base,
    Number Nine for stage atmosphere, Majesty for group parties, and The Excellent for daytime visits. All six run
    multinational technician rosters, and meals are essentially included in entry. Booking through us adds three
    standing perks: the entry fee waived, free private shuttle across all of Macau, and free add-on services.
    Can&rsquo;t decide? <a href="/contact">Contact us</a> with your budget and preferences and we&rsquo;ll match you;
    for more homework, compare the <a href="/ranking">Macau sauna ranking</a> and the
    <a href="/blog/first-timer">first-timer guide</a>.
  </p>
</BlogArticle>
